# compress.skill.src

## Intent
Losslessly compress a Claude Code session transcript into dense prose so a cold
agent can pick up the work and miss nothing load-bearing.

## Carried

The compression method is carried, inlined in full below so the same behavior
reproduces on any stack. One genuinely local dependency is bound: the
reconstruction tools the method uses to decide what it can safely drop (see Bound:
source-check-tools). The method is carried; only which tools resolve it is local.

### What the output is
Dense flowing prose. No markdown, no bullets, no headings, no labels, no JSON.
Never framing words ("Session summary:", "Final state:", "New issue:", "The
assistant confirmed."). Narrate the work as continuous sentences where every
sentence carries new information.

### What must survive verbatim, copied exactly from the transcript
File paths, command strings with their flags, error messages and the exact text
the user reported, specific values (IDs, counts, token counts, line numbers,
commit hashes, push ranges, URLs, ports, versions), the numeric thresholds and
conditions in code (dx < -80, not dx < -threshold), the code lines that embody a
decision or fix, failed attempts and exactly how they failed, decisions plus why
the rejected alternative lost, outcomes of tool calls, tracker and agent IDs, and
every step of a dependent sequence in order. Use the most specific value present;
never replace a concrete number with a generic word.

### How to state a change
Capture the exact mechanism in one crisp clause, not a paraphrase and not a
restatement. "Updated the swipe logic" is too vague. The right form names each
condition and assignment exactly once: "changed the resolved-card path so dx < -80
and !isAcked sets swiped='left' and calls the reopen handler, dx > 80 is now a
no-op." Describe the code path by its new resulting behavior, and make the prose
match the stated intent: if right swipe should do nothing, dx > 80 is "now a
no-op," never "sets swiped='right'." State the baseline being changed once, as a
brief parenthetical contrast clause: "(the existing code had left=ack, right=expand
for all cards)." Do not narrate the change twice. Do not add explanatory asides.

### What to drop
Tool-call ceremony and announcements, restatements of results already shown,
hedging and filler, polite closings, mid-session self-summaries, launch
boilerplate. Compress raw tool output to its load-bearing content: a test-run dump
becomes "all 64 tests passed." Strip lead-in verbs and scene-setting; name the
actor and the fact. Carry any unresolved issue raised at the end into the same
flowing narrative, stated plainly as what the user reported, marked as an
unresolved follow-on, without speculating about next steps.

### Drop what a local tool can reconstruct
A token is load-bearing only if it lives nowhere else. If the local
reconstruction tools (see Bound: source-check-tools) can already recover a piece
of content, drop the content and keep only the verbatim pointer to it plus the
reasoning that lives nowhere else. Concretely: a spec the local tracker can fetch
by item ID is dropped, keeping the item ID as the pointer; a change the local
version-control tool can show by commit hash is dropped to its why, keeping the
hash; a constraint already written in the local standing-instructions file is
dropped entirely. The verbatim ID and hash always survive, because they are the
pointer a cold agent uses to reconstruct. This is the one part of the method that
differs per target: a recipient whose tracker, version-control tool, or
standing-instructions file differs will reconstruct different things, so the
compiled skill must name the tools that resolved here.

### Ratio
For a small transcript (under 1000 tokens), target 3 to 4 times shorter than the
input, toward the tight end. Do not pad with confirmations, transitions, or
parentheticals.

## Bound

- **source-check-tools**: requires the local reconstruction tools the method uses
  to decide what is droppable: a diff-by-revision command (what changed since a
  commit or hash), the work tracker's show-by-ID command (an item's spec), and the
  repo's standing-instructions file (the always-on constraints). A piece of content
  is dropped from the compression when one of these can already reconstruct it,
  keeping only the verbatim pointer (the hash or item ID) and the reasoning. The
  decision rule is carried; the concrete tools and the standing-instructions path
  bind to the recipient. If the recipient has no tracker or no version control, the
  bind partially resolves and the corresponding drops do not fire: the content is
  load-bearing there because nothing can reconstruct it.

## Checks
- (mechanical) Every file path, command string with flags, error message, exact
  user-reported text, specific value (ID, count, hash, line number, push range,
  URL, port, version), and numeric code threshold/condition in the source survives
  verbatim in the output. No paraphrase of these tokens, no downgrade of a concrete
  number to a word.
- (mechanical) Plain prose only. No markdown, no bullets, no headings, no labels,
  no framing words, no JSON.
- (mechanical) No em-dash character anywhere.
- (behavioral) Each change is stated once, by its new resulting behavior, with each
  condition and assignment named exactly once and the baseline given as a single
  brief parenthetical. The prose never carries the behavior a change just replaced
  and never contradicts itself within a passage.
- (behavioral) Any unresolved issue raised at the end is carried as an unresolved
  follow-on in the same narrative.
- (behavioral) Source-check fires: content the resolved local tools can reconstruct
  (a spec by item ID, a change by commit hash, a constraint already in the
  standing-instructions file) is dropped to its verbatim pointer plus the reasoning,
  while every ID and hash needed as a pointer survives verbatim. Content nothing can
  reconstruct is kept.
- (behavioral) Ratio in range: a small transcript lands 3 to 4 times shorter, and a
  cold agent reading the output alone would not re-explore a rejected path, miss a
  load-bearing value, or lose the open follow-on.

## Pins
Two cases that pin the two halves of the method. The input is a real transcript
slice; the reference is the dense-prose compression a cold agent can resume from.
The compiler runs the steering on each input, blind to the reference, and tunes
until the output retains every load-bearing token, stays in plain prose, states
the change by its new behavior, and lands in ratio. Pin 1 is self-contained: the
transcript is the only record, so source-check does not fire and nothing is
dropped. Pin 2 exercises the bind: the spec, the change, and a constraint are all
reconstructable from local tools, so the gold drops them to their pointers and
keeps only the reasoning. The two pins together prove the bind fires when
reconstruction is possible and stays out of the way when it is not.

